Subject:  2015 Summer Schools in Software Development and Molecular Respons=
e Properties

Dear Fellow Theoretical Chemists:

I am pleased to announce two Summer Schools to be held here at Virginia Tec=
h this year that may be of interest to you or your colleagues.

Third Annual Software Summer School, June 22-July 1:<http://s2i2.org/school=
_2015/index.html>  This NSF-sponsored Summer School targets first- and seco=
nd-year graduate students whose Ph.D. research requires significant program=
ming skills.  The School, which is part of the sustainable software initiat=
ive led by the SICM2 Project, will cover a range of software design and opt=
imization, including programming fundamentals, numerical libraries, paralle=
l computing, and GPU/accelerator algorithms.

http://s2i2.org/school_2015/

Interested students should submit an application consisting of a CV, letter=
 of support, and a brief description of their research and how it would ben=
efit from the advanced programming skills offered by the School.  Students =
accepted to the program will need only provide their own transportation to =
the Virginia Tech campus; all other expenses, including room, board, and in=
structional costs will be covered by the School.  (Note that only student a=
t U.S. institutions are eligible for participation in this year's Software =
Summer School.)

----------------------

Molecular Response Properties Summer School, June 29-July 3:<http://www.the=
ory.chem.vt.edu/response/index.html>  Much of our understanding of molecule=
s and materials is derived from their responses to electromagnetic fields =
=96 from high-resolution spectroscopic analyses for the identification of m=
olecules in interstellar space, to magnetic resonance imaging used in medic=
al diagnostics, to non-linear fiber optics employed in telecommunications. =
This school will focus on the quantum mechanical theories underlying both w=
eak- and strong-field responses, in absorption, emission, and scattering, a=
t a level appropriate for graduate students and postdoctoral researchers.

http://www.theory.chem.vt.edu/response/

The School will be taught by Profs. Patrick Norman (Link=F6ping U., Sweden)=
, Trond Saue (U. Toulouse), Kenneth Ruud (Arctic University of Norway), and=
 Daniel Crawford (Virginia Tech).   Interested participants may register at=
 the above website (no application process is otherwise required).  The $55=
0 registration fee includes room, board, and instructional expenses, but no=
t transportation costs.

Best regards,
--
Prof. T. Daniel Crawford
crawdad@vt.edu<mailto:crawdad@vt.edu>


